caption:
This fine body of inspirational people, dug deep around a successful 30 mile yomp today. We as a team could not be more proud, or grateful to have accompanied them on their own personal journey across Dartmoor. With a wide age range from as a young as 13 all the way up to 62, it was a privilege to witness. We would also like to give a big thank you and a special mention to Diane Warwick who persisted on doing her own 30 miler (31) at home after picking up a niggling injury not so long ago. In general, a huge thank you to everybody involved, tonight brings a well deserved rest .

caption:
Found these floating in the waves today at the beach.
And if you look really closely at my hand, you can see the sparkly residue of the plastic wrapper.
Delightful.
**
Is this really what you want your kids to swim in?
Is this what you want the ocean animals to be surrounded by? Or accidentally consume?
Is convenience so important that you can't say no to that plastic encased water or juice or soda?
**
Planning ahead is easy.
A small cooler filled with ice packs and reusable water bottles.
Snacks in reusable containers.
BASIC.
Convenience is what has gotten us into this mess.
And the mess is not going to go away until we start re-evaluating our needs for convenience and weigh it against how much we care about a livable future for our kids.

caption:
"The highlight for me was the look on every single persons face when they looked in the back of that lorry and saw just how many pots had been collected. I was able to see, again and again, everyone suddenly feel that same pride I had been feeling all weekend. It was magical and totally inspring" ğŸ˜.
.
This weekend, 4-5th May 2019, Trevisker Garden Centre Beach Guardian and The Ocean Recovery Project hosted 'The Great Pot Amnesty' at @trevisker_garden_centre â™»ï¸.
.
Over the weekend, we have been encouraging the people of Cornwall (and even further afield), to get out into their garden sheds, dust off those cobwebs and pull out their old plastic gardening pots and seed trays. We were asking for these to be brought up to the Garden Centre, where we were collecting them in 'Lola - the Lovely Orange Lorry' ğŸŒ³ğŸŒ±ğŸ§¡.
.
Tomorrow morning, Lola is going to be collected by The Ocean Recovery Project. .
All of the pots and seed trays that were collected will be recycled.
.
You cannot recycle these plastics kerbside.
.
This weekend has made a huge impact on all involved. None of us expected to finish today with an overflowing container old and unwanted plastic pots, many having travelled so many miles to get to us.
.
Thank you, and well done to everyone that was involved.
.
To find out more what will happen to these pots, check out The @oceanrecoveryproject and @odysseyinnovation.
.
#iamabeachguardian

caption:
My 2 year old leading the way and showing us all what we should be doing!

I am so proud to see how educated my little boy is already at the age of 2 - he will tell you that he goes to the beach to clean up the rubbish to save the whales and sharks; he can determine what the rubbish is and how it shouldn't be at the beach ... how does he know all of this? Because I have shown him because I am a parent and that is my responsibility.

Seeing how Kavai understands all of this has made me even more passionate to educate our generation as there really is no excuse - if a 2 year knows what belongs on the beach and what doesn't then all of us can educate our children to.

We all live on this planet and many of us take it for granted but the time has come when all of us should be grateful that we get to call this incredible planet our home!! #bethechange #ocean #ocean

caption: In about 2 months I'll be moving from Barcelona to a town in The Netherlands that's not close to the sea, so I won't be able to continue my beach clean-ups on a regular basis. This means that while we still live here I'll be doing a lot of beach cleanups. I set a goal to do Cleanups on 7 different beaches in the area over the next few weeks. I started yesterday at Sitges beach. In the 2,5 hours on the beach I filled up one big shopping bag and 6 smaller buckets and after that there was still a lot of trash left on the beach, but I had to leave. It sometimes really frustrates me that I'm never able to fully clean a beach and that I always have to leave trash behind on the beach..

caption: The first image is the trash we picked up on the beach in Florida. For little over an hour we did a beach clean up. I wouldn't have felt right enjoying the beach without doing that. We as humans want to enjoy the beauty of it all and that is fine. But our actions cause trauma to the animals in the ocean. I just want to urge you ALL to do the right thing. Grab a bag and pick up some of this trash while you are out enjoying a beach day. It doesn't take much honestly, just your time. It pains me to see what the animals have to go through because of us. We can make the ocean healthy again. It starts with us. You may not like the videos I have posted but this is reality. We should be more mindful of our actions. Clean up the beaches. We can change things one garbage bag at a time. Just start! caption:
No plastic here! Every trip to the beach there seems to be a plastic beach toy left on the sand from someone who had been there previously. I totally get how this happens and we may have done the same in the past. We have had plastic buckets and spades before and they break so easily that new ones are purchased every summer.
.

For a while now, we have bought items that have multi uses that the kids can take to the beach also. Mia has some garden equipment like digging tools made of wood and metal and a tin watering can. Today we took these ikea kids metal kitchen tools, these are great for the bath too! My mum is buying some @plantoysuk flower pots for Romans birthday as they can be used in so many ways including beach, bath, play dough, mud.
. 
If we were to leave any of these items on the beach ğŸ˜² which I really hope doesn't happen, then at least they won't break down into micro plastics and go straight into the sea.
.

2 minute beach clean completed today by Mia ğŸ’š

caption: Let Carl sleep in this morning. So after getting my espresso at Pipes, I headed to Beacons Beach and did beach clean up. I intended to do just the Beacons area, but the tide was reasonably low and the weather was in my favor..... so I scoured the beach from the north edge of Beacons to the stairs of Stonesteps. Fortunately it wasnâ€™t too bad this morning as it was mainly smalls like bits of styrofoam and plastic water bottle caps. The most interesting thing was the little sail jelly things that washed up in various stages of loosing their blue gummy parts. If you didnâ€™t know what they were, you would assume they were bits of plastic washing up. Nope. I remember when I went on a trip up the CA coast when I was about 20 and saw beaches with hundreds of these guys washed up. On my way back to the car at Beacons, I happened upon two sweet frames someone had put on the curb. Yoink!!!! More frames to use for my art show pieces! Nice! Anyway, time to get back to work! #beachcleanup #beaconsbeachcleanup #stonestepsbeach #beachcleanupis247365 #trashpinchers #washedupsealife #encinitasbeachcleanup #leucadianative

caption:
"Preserving our Planet and it's People, to Protect our Purpose", is one of the major Causes Decathlon as a whole is fighting for today. 
Decathlon Ghana in our bid to make sports accessible to all, continued with our monthly Beach Cleanup Exercise at the Coco Beach in Nungua last Saturday 27th April 2019. As always we collaborated with *Plastic Punch*, a private NGO, we have partnered with for our environmental and sanitation projects, and whose vision is aligned with Decathlon Ghana's vision of preserving the environment.
Indeed it was a fun filled event as we collectively *PUNCHED THE PLASTICS* off the beach, *EDUCATED* the community on the importance of keeping our Beaches clean, and of course, *PRACTISED SEVERAL SPORTS* together on the clean Beach.
We entreat all like minded organisations and groups to join us on the last Saturday of every month for this worthy cause. 
Below are some images.
Thanks to Decathlon Ghana our USERS through SPORTS will have more PLEASURE, better HEALTH and a better SOCIAL INTEGRATION thus LIVE LIFE to the FULLEST.

OUR KPI: Increase life expectancy at birth from 67 to 77 years.

#Like and #Share to support the movement.

.

.
Do yourself a favor, no more excuses, give them a follow and get involved - a hands-on approach to making a difference if there ever was one. We need to keep our oceans clean, so make sure you take home any rubbish from trips to the beach!

caption:
"Mum, I can't look mad for too long!" she said when I took a photo of Cecilia at the end of our #beachcleanup at @alohasurf.nl today.
That is because she is a nice human being. And because she wants good for everyone, including animals and plants, the beach she loves to play at and the sea that splashes up against the shore.
But when you empty a bag full of trash, including tiny threads of plastic that look like sea weed, soda cans, styrofoam chunks, cigarette stubs, plastic wrappings and spiky plastic forks ... just after 45 minutes of weeding through the dunes and the sand ... well, then you will feel mad the least. Mad about the people who didn't care to find a proper bin for their waste.
But also you will feel guilty and ashamed for consuming and producing so much trash yourself. For continuing to do so day after day because it is convenient. Because it is how our world is programmed today.
So right now, I am sitting with this mix of feelings. Looking at my daughter who is proud of having done good today. Knowing that there is a long way ahead of us. And so little time.
.
.
.
#nofilter #beachcleanup #whatthetrash #thereisnoplanetb  #scheveningenbeach #alohasurf #cleanyourshitup

caption:
Yesterday my daughter and I did our usual beach walk; she was armed with her bucket and spade to build castles, I was armed with a bag to pick up any rubbish we might encounter at the beach. -
There had been a storm the night before and the storm water had run off from the streets to the beach. I was devastated to realise that my small bag was never going to be big enough to fit all of the rubbish that had been flushed down to the sand.
-
Feeling helpless, I filled my bag and left the rest behind. It was a feeling of utter frustration; whatever I could do would never be enough to make a difference. -
I havenâ€™t been able to stop thinking about this sight at the beach. Iâ€™ve been reading and finding ways to do more, thinking how my small actions could perhaps become something more significant.
-
I am not pretending to be perfect, but the least I can do is to send out this little message to all of you out there - and hope that perhaps we can do something bigger together.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

caption: Even though we live in one of Australiaâ€™s more remote locations, the Torres Strait Islands, it doesnâ€™t make us immune to the impacts of large scale consumerism. We visit this part of our island at the very least once a fortnight and are more shocked every visit with the scale of marine debris deposits. From thongs, toothbrushes, lighters and oil drums to childrenâ€™s toys, berthing hawsers, water and detergent bottles and indistinguishable micro plastics - weâ€™ve seen it all. Much of the debris can be traced to international trawling vessels and relatively close neighbouring countries - having said that, much comes from closer to home. Itâ€™s hard to keep caring when it seems so largely out of our hands but after all, in the end, our actions do all count and weâ€™ll keep doing our part by lessening our consumer footprints, closing the loop and educating awareness ğŸŒ´ #marinedebris #reducereuserecycle #closetheloop #beachcleanup #consumerism #hornisland #torresstrait #plasticpollution #stopthesource

Sahabat peduli Pantai , bukan hanya pantai cangkring yang butuh uluran tangan kita , ayo bersama sama membawa perubahan , ikuti #reresikpantaiminggu8 , dan gerakan ini masih terbuka untuk menerima donasi dari teman teman ..

A bit of early morning beach combing along the Lang Lang foreshore.

I have recovered some 30+ kg of rubbish, at a guess. I donâ€™t expect I got it all, but I got everything last I saw; including hundreds of metres of fishing line, hooks, lures, jigs etc.

caption:
@gretathunberg recently addressed the UK parliament, saying â€˜I know many of you donâ€™t want to listen to us â€“ you say we are just children. But weâ€™re only repeating the message of the united climate science.â€™â£
â£
She pointed out the UK shale gas fracking industry, the expansion of North Sea oil and gas fields, the building of more airports and planning permission of a brand new coal mine as â€˜absurdâ€™, as well as the UKs â€˜creativeâ€™ carbon accounting. â£
â£
We are not doing enough, we talk about climate change seriously, but this is not reflected in our actions.â£
â£
The greenhouse gas emissions curve is still increasing. Greta says that every time we make a decision, we should think about how it will affect the curve. Indeed, she says we should ask ourselves â€˜have we got the carbon budget to spare to go through with this?â€™â£
â£
We know climate change is a real and dangerous problem. This is a fact. Weâ€™ve known it for years. We know that we must reduce our dependency on fossil fuels and make the economy more circular. â£
â£
We havenâ€™t quite figured out all the solutions yet, and this is where political inertia stems from. As Greta says â€˜we have to start treating the crisis like a crisis â€“ and act even if we donâ€™t have all of the solutionsâ€™.â£
â£
Stopping climate change will require a lot of thinking and change to our economies and governments. We donâ€™t know the answer yet, but we will find a way. Anything we all put our mind to, we can achieve.â£
â£

caption:
Why should we care?
.
.
.
A lot of people I know just don't seem to care that we use resources faster than the Earth can replenish them. They don't care that we're unsustainable, that we're killing our home and the home of animals, that we're seeing extinction of animals, that our air and water is polluted, that we create so much waste
They don't care.
ğŸŒŠ
ğŸŒŠ
ğŸŒŠ
But I do, and I know I'm not alone. So take a moment and ask yourself "Why do I care about the environment?" And let it strengthen your resolve to making environmental change. ğŸ 
ğŸ 
ğŸ 
I care because I'd be ridiculous not to. This is our home, let's not burn it down recklessly.

caption:
Beach cleanup day! No matter where you are in the world, on average you will find about one ton of garbage per kilometer of beach. 
We joined a sizable army of volunteers today in an effort to clean up one of our local sand banks. Some of the fishing nets were so deeply buried and entangled that we had to cut them in half before we could drag them back to the collection point, though most items were small enough that we could put them on our trailers.

All in all, we filled up two massive containers with a vast array of marine trash, from fishing nets to empty bottles of household products and car tires.
~
#iceland #trashtag #beachcleanup #naturelovers #superjeep #nissanpatrol

Goodbye disposable plastic, paper and aluminum films!
The social cooperative Sonda has created "Apepak" a compound of cotton fiber jojoba oil and beeswax, which doesn't pollute and can be reused 100 times per single sheet.
Apepak is made of organic or recycled cotton from the leftovers of Italian textile laboratories. Beeswax, pine resin and jojoba oil are supplied by Italian beekeepers and companies.
Using Apepak could save 9 sq. Km of plastic wrappers per year.

caption:
Beach clean findings from Cuckmere Haven for day 4 of #36adaymay. 
This is another exercise from the Photographer's Playbook: Sara Cwynar's brief to find a collection of related objects and photograph them in different arrangements.

I used my beach clean findings from yesterday, and attempted a flat lay. This style of photography is alien to me: it's deliberate and considered, which I don't normally do. It was tricky to get the light right, keep my shadow out of the shot and the background clear of sand. It was easier than I thought to come up with 36 different configurations though, and I enjoyed the slow, methodical way of working. I'm pleased with the results.

There's a few of my favourite images here, and all 36 in the video.

caption:
In 2014, I made an outreach table at one of my favorite places in the #BahamaOutIslands to share information on the invisible issue of ocean plastic pollution. A core group of us had been working on researching and exposing the problem since the 90s. I'm encouraged to see that while there is much to be done, ocean plastic pollution has entered the global conversation as a top environmental concern. This summer we're developing strategies for Wildblusea based on lessons learned in piloting Blue Mind infused ocean conservation initiatives around the North Atlantic the past 5 years. All hands on deck!

caption:
Mangrove challenge - 90 minutes of clean up, 3 volunteers on one mangrove equipped with knives in 30Â°c yet it's just "moderately clean"

Mangroves act as a buffer between the sea and the land, it reduces the impact of waves but now they work double time and also stop the marine debris which gets entangled in their branches and choke their roots as they shoot above the ground which is slowly killing them. 
Mangroves are one of the important habitat for marine ecosystem and serve as breeding spots for many species which play an important part in the marine and coastal ecosystem.

But thanks to our recklessness they are struggling to thrive and are choking to death in a grave of orphan plastic.

caption:
.This is not a nice  video showing you lovely landscapes, beaches and other places! .Though I am not an activist or moralist, I had to film these little sequences  about my findings on the beach in Usedom (Baltic Sea) when doing my daily morning walks. .The beaches on the island Usedom are cleaned every morning with a lot of effort and enthousiasm. .I could see it personally  with my eyes every day during my stay. .
.The striking thing I found out is that most of the items I found are a mixture between products focussing on the "to-go-consumption" or on the "single use". And the question I put to myself was: if I was a fish in the ocean, could I be able to avoid it? No chance at all!  After all, I concluded to pick it up and to throw it in the rubbish containers placed on the beach. 
This is only a very little contribution, but even better than doing nothing!

I just found a flyer - it is called "The Usedom project: Beach clean up" on 17th of May 2019. It is the biggest project for sustainability organized by young people in Germany.

caption:
What an absolute beautiful beach.. swipe to see what we found.
As you may know, @metalnotmeat , and my little men and I do a beach bbq every week, (plant based of course!) and do a beach clean up for @take3forthesea.
We go to a different beach every week and we are always surprised by how much we find, even when the beach appears clean on the surface.
But Murray's Beach today just blew us all away. 
Cigarette butts, fishing line galore, bait bags, plastic bottles... All devastating for marine life. Left by lazy fishermen who fish from the rocks here.
I cannot understand how humans can come to such a beautiful place and leave their mess. What they leave pollutes the oceans, and kills the animals that call it home.
Please leave nothing but footprints, and @take3forthesea while you are there.
I think we took about 333 today! .
.
.

caption: During the course of our 6 hour day at the beach, we watched probably 40-50 people walk or kayak past giant rocks to see caves and a waterfall. We filled a bag today with old buoys, PET bottles, an old flip flop and random pieces of plastic with hardly any effort. Of course others came back empty handed. What is dental erosion ?
As hard as tooth enamel is, the high acid content in many fruits and fruit juices can cause it to weaken and demineralize over time... The goods news is you don't have to give up fruit in order to prevent erosion. .

Here are a simple few tips to keep your teeth healthy while maintaining your vitamin C requirement: .

1.  Use a straw when drinking fruit juices. .

2. Rinse with water after eating fruit to dilute the acids in your mouth, and wait at least 30 minutes before brushing to give your enamel time to resettle. .

3. Keep your enamel strong by brushing with fluoridated toothpaste.. .
.

4. Eat cheese after your fruit. This raises the pH levels in your mouth and increases saliva production, which also helps neutralize acids. .
.

SCAREY FACT
In the UK almost a quarter (24.7%) of 5 year olds have tooth decay, so 1 in 4 children will have tooth decay when they start school - ACT NOW .

caption:
Norway has beautiful nature everywhere you look and I especially love #northernnorway Â´s white sandy beaches, turquoise waters, and tall, majestic, snowy mountains. But truth is that also here, the ocean, beaches, rivers, and coastlines are getting trashed with plastic and waste created and caused by humans. I don't think we mean to cause harm, to cause pollution,  we are just following along with what is, "mindlessly" living in a broken system. With that said, good things are happening and action is taken because we are waking up to the issues. Today is the official #Strandryddedagen in Norway, a part of #Strandryddeuka (beach clean up week) Over 1000Â´s of volunteers join @holdnorgerent in Norway's biggest collective clean-up initiative, to clean up the beaches, lakes, rivers and even the bottom of the sea. This is an inspiring, important and proactive way to help heal the planet and let nature heal you - It might not seem like it helps, but it surely does when everybody gets together. If anything we gain more awareness around what kind of trash that is out there. We also create community and inspire each other. I personally had a lot of fun running around on the beaches and streams here in Lofoten collecting all kinds of weird trash and things. Find and join a cleanup near you by using this link https://holdnorgerent.no/ryddeportalen/â£ or visit my partner in creativity @eplehusetno as they provide clean-up kits  at any of their service centers located all over Norway- use the link https://eplehuset.no/strandryddedagenâ£

caption:
At this yearâ€™s cleanups, look for our fun new poster filled with all kinds of things to learn about plastics - like this one all about the life cycle of a plastic bottle! â™»ï¸
â€¢
We know single use plastics can become marine debris and what those effects normally are, but what about production effects?
â€¢
Well, just in case you needed another reason to support #dontdrillnc, in order to satisfy the 31.2 BILLION gallons of bottled water purchased in 2006, 17 BILLION gallons of oil were required! #DidYouKnow that if you take a standard plastic water bottle, and fill it about an 1/8 full with crude oil, thatâ€™s a pretty good estimate of how much it took to produce the plastic bottle ğŸ¤¢ yikes.
â€¢
Now...onto #ClimateChange. To produce those 31.2 billion gallons worth of plastic bottles, 2.5 MILLION TONS of CO2 were released into the atmosphere during production ğŸ˜³ This CO2 either depletes our protective ozone layer, is absorbed by trees (deforestation is causing us to not have enough to absorb it all ğŸ˜­), OR is absorbed by the ocean. When this happens, ocean temperature rises, ocean acidification occurs, all kinds of crazy bad things happen that cause more frequent severe weather events, harm animals, etc etc etc doom and gloom ugh
â€¢
Now...#WaterScarcity ğŸ’§ Itâ€™s a real problem for people, animals, and the environment as a whole. So itâ€™s a HUGE bummer that one plastic water bottle requires 3x the amount of water to produce it - LAME ğŸ˜’ â€¢
These water bottles are then shipped all over the place, using more fuel, releasing more CO2 emissions...
â€¢
FINALLY, we have that nice lil water bottle in our hands, we chug it in 5 minutes and then......thatâ€™s it! We pitch it in the trash ğŸ—‘ â€¢
This lil water bottle ends up in a landfill or the ocean (letâ€™s say there no recycling in this pseudo hypothetical land) where it takes 450 YEARS to decompose (at best). It never goes away. It continuously breaks down into smaller and smaller pieces, but still manages to be harmful to wildlife and humans at just about any size.
â€¢
But theyâ€™re convenient and I was thirsty for 5 minutes ğŸ¤·ğŸ½â€â™€ï¸
â€¢
[continued in comment below â˜ºï¸]

The good news about biodegradable/compostable plastic is it is typically made from plants rather than petroleum. The bad news is you need a large industrial composting facility to create the ideal conditions in which to break down these types of plastics. In fact, some recycling facilities consider PLA (made from corn) a contaminant. 
Shifting to â€œbetterâ€ plastic is less of a solution than shifting away from all plastic altogether. 
Think reusable, not disposable. (Photo via @plasticpollutes)

caption:
Please join Sea Shepherd Long Island Chapter-less Group on Sunday, May 19th at Jones Beach - Field 6 for a beach cleanup. 
Millions of pounds of garbage are dumped into the oceans every year threatening marine wildlife. Fish and other sea animals can ingest large pieces of plastic that clog their intestines, or they can become entangled in plastic and suffocate. This is your chance to help save lives and make a difference. 
We will meet by the concession stand tables and clean the beach from 12:00â€“2:00PM. Bags and gloves will be provided.

Donâ€™t forget to dress accordingly.Â Â Please wear a Sea Shepherd shirt if you have one.

We look forward to seeing you there.

For more information please email SeaShepherdLongIsland@gmail.com

.
How It Started: Operation Rich Coast started in their local community, Quepos Village, doing small clean ups. The group now promotes and organizes cleanups throughout the country and have founded National Cleanup Day, which this year united more than 1,500 people in 45 different locations simultaneously throughout the country.
.
Where Are The Cleanups?: Operation Rich Coastâ€™s platform promotes the initiatives of every type of cleanup, including urban areas, beaches, rivers, parks, and more.
.

caption:
This rapid decline of coral needs to be treated with the importance and urgency that it deserves. Corals are not only habitat to some of the greatest diversity of marine species and protect our coastlines but they also help US by assisting in carbon and nitrogen fixing, and along with other marine plants produce 70% of the earths oxygen!!
â€”âŒPLASTICâŒ suffocates and blocks the sunlight of these corals AND  increases deadly diseases in coral causing them to die and bleach by 89%!! â€”Coral is so important to balance in marine life, and also in our lives! Reduce your plastic consumption and help clean up beaches and go snorkeling for straws and plastics (strawkling) to make a difference!! Another big thing you can do is use reef safe sunscreens because along with plastic, the other chemicals that are effecting corals are from things like our sunscreen when we go for a swim! ğŸŒğŸ¬

caption:
My #36adaymay exercise was depressingly easy today. I went to Cuckmere Haven and took a picture of every piece of rubbish I found. I got 36 photos in minutes. The photos are simple - I've arranged them into colour groups here. 
I should say, I actually kind of like beach cleaning. Yes, it's awful that it's there. But I like being outside, doing something useful.

I picked up all of the rubbish up (obvs) and will take some different pictures of them tomorrow... #beachcleanup #2minutebeachclean #plasticpollution #beachcombing #recycle #beachcleaning #cleanseas #beachclean #cuckmerehaven #sussex #eastsussex #olympus #olympusomd #olympuscreators #photographersplaybook

Hello from Save the Children India, Delhi Chapter!

Plastic as a material is not harmful. What is harmful is when we donâ€™t dispose it in the correct way and it stays in the environment damaging lives.  The power to stop plastic litter in cities, oceans, rivers and waterways lies in our hands. 
United Way Mumbai with the support of Hindustan Unilever Limited (HUL) organized a beach clean-up drive under the â€œPlastic Banega Fantasticâ€ campaign. The plastic waste collected during the campaign will be segregated and recycled by HUL to create products such as benches, boats, planters and spectacles and donated to needy people.

Save the Children India participated in the beach clean-up drive to reduce marine pollution at the ITO Chhat Ghat with around 60 volunteers.

caption:
A little bit of rain couldn't stop these volunteers from keeping our communities clean and green!

In honor of Earth Day, we held our annual multi-town cleanup which included 19 beaches, parks, and playgrounds across Marblehead, Swampscott, Nahant, and Salem on Sunday, April 28. 
Our effort consisted of 224 volunteers, 123 of whom were under the age of 17.  Collectively these volunteers netted over 60 bags of trash and piles of debris. Among notable items: 2 golf clubs, 3 beach chairs, a traffic cone, 2 lobster traps, a car bumper, a rubber snake, a plastic steering wheel, 3 shoes, $2 in loose change, and 4 hypodermic needles.

@salemsoundcoastwatch shared their knowledge and leadership at Stramski and Philips beach, and respective Towns & Cities helped support our effort by supplying trash bags and gloves.

Following the cleanup, volunteers stopped by our office and enjoyed pizza from our friends at @livelongandpizza . 
Thank you to all the volunteers who joined us this year! We are grateful to have you as part of our Community of Doers!

#CommunityOfDoers #SPURgooddeeds #volunteer #communityservice #earthdayeveryday #beachcleanup #EarthDay

caption:
THE END IS NEAR!
.
ALL YEAR, it has been a real-time environmental catastrophe. The Great Barrier Reef, an unparalleled ecological treasure that supports all sorts of sea life and a range of human needs, not to mention a huge tourist economy, has seen the largest coral die-off ever recorded. If this were a rare event, separated by many years from the next big die-off, the reef would rebound. But in the age of climate change, scientists say this and other tragedies are frighteningly likely to be compounded.
.
Experts have been tracking the destruction for months,Â announcing their final conclusionsÂ Nov. 29, 2018. They found that across a long stretch of the northern end of the reef, an average of 67 percent of the coral died, according to aerial and diver observations. In these zones, the reefâ€™s lively colors have been replaced by antiseptic white of â€œbleachedâ€ coral. Though weather events helped spare other areas this degree of destruction, the reefâ€™s northern portions had been the most pristine.
.
In this case, the problem appears to have been water temperature, which wasÂ up to two degrees warmerÂ than the normal summer peak. This threw off the delicate balance between the coral organisms and the algae that provide them sustenance. Natural variability may have played some role in raising the temperature â€” it was an El NiÃ±o year, which means the Pacific Ocean was hotter. But global warming probably set the scene. Australian scientistsÂ concludedÂ that this yearâ€™s coral crisis was rendered far more likely because of climate-change-related ocean warmth. As the planet continues to warm, human influence will be more and more likely to interact with natural variation in dangerous ways. Among other things, that means all that dead coral may not have a chance to rebound.(Text taken from The Washington Post)
.
.
.

caption:
The 4Wild Group (led by @rspb_love_nature Shetland) cleaned 22 bags from the beaches around Gletness, Nesting. 
The majority of bruck was ropes and net alongside two huge floats filled with tiny polystyrene balls. One float had partially broken which made the coastline on one beach look like it had been snowing! The team intend to contact local seafood firms for collection of these two large floats to avoid any further pollution from them so we are hopeful this will be a good outcome. Other interesting finds included a sun-baked pipefish, lobster tags and a metal tin of chocolate flavoured body paint! ğŸ™ˆ

This was a more remote area so the group would like to thank the locals that organised bruck removal with a quad to take it to the collection point. Great work everyone! ğŸ’š

Ik ga zo lekker bij jullie #binnenkijken want er zijn zo veel nieuwe accounts om te ontdekken.  Heb me opgegeven als vrijwilliger voor de beach clean up in Noordwijk georganiseerd door @novasol. Dus straks handjes uit de mouw en duimen dat het ochtend zonnetje blijft plakken hier aan het strand. Mocht je in de buurt van Noordwijk zijn en nog niets te doen hebben vandaag. Check de website van www.NLvoorelkaar.nl en meld je aan. Dit is de eerste keer dat ik vrijwilligers werk ga doen. Ben heel benieuwd!
Doen jullie ook wel eens #vrijwilligerswerk? Vertel me over je ervaring. Want dit groentje heeft nog een hoop bezwaren en vooroordelen om zich overheen te zetten. Terwijl er in de basis toch niets mooiers bestaat als je de mogelijkheid hebt om andere te helpen. 
Anyhoe.... wat je ook gaat doen vandaag. Doe het met een glimlach en maak er een mooie dag van! 
Liefs, Reina

PLASTIC STATION â™»ï¸
â €
â €â €Each bag or plastic cup that we take out of the water, the sand, or the river potentially means a rescued turtle or a bird. And at the same time, every plastic bag or plastic cup that we send to be recycled means some good and some profit.Â So one of our project is #PlasticStation (project PlasticBack.com)
â €
1ï¸âƒ£ PLASTIC STATION - local station for the plastic waste recycling, with the release of finished products (building blocks, materials for road construction, playgrounds, etc.)
â €
â €â €Required amount #PlasticStation: $ 20,000
When: July 2019
â €
â €â €And the best addition to Plastic Station will be another our project - #RiverFilter
â €
2ï¸âƒ£ RIVER FILTER - river  filtration (energy autonomous) system to collect garbage for its subsequent separation into organic and nonorganic. Nonorganic garbage will go to Plastic Station and organic waste will go to #PosKompos
â €
3ï¸âƒ£ POS KOMPOS - organic waste recycling station for the manufacture of fertilized soil.
â €
â €â €Required amount of #PosKompos: $ 20,000
When: August 2019
â €
â €â €Thus, all these 3 components together will allow to recycle ~ 100% of garbage that will be collected in neighbouring villages, caught from the river and (in the future) collected from all villagers.
â €
â €â €First #PlasticStation designed by @bluemoloko studio and  intends to stay on the river bank at @BLAGO_Retreat_Village ( Indonesia / Bali / Gianyar ).
